WEBVTT

1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
TED：你应该相信你的第一印象吗？
Should you trust your first impression

2
00:00:06,979 --> 00:00:08,722
Imagine you're at a football game
想象你在看一场足球赛

3
00:00:08,722 --> 00:00:11,206
when this obnoxious guy sits next to you.
旁边坐着一个讨厌鬼

4
00:00:11,206 --> 00:00:11,906
He's loud,
他讲话很大声

5
00:00:11,906 --> 00:00:13,240
he spills his drink on you,
饮料洒到你

6
00:00:13,240 --> 00:00:14,995
and he makes fun of your team.
他还嘲笑你支持的球队

7
00:00:14,995 --> 00:00:17,226
Days later, you're walking in the park
几天之后，你在公园散步

8
00:00:17,226 --> 00:00:19,823
when suddenly it starts to pour rain.
突然下了一场大雨

9
00:00:19,823 --> 00:00:21,130
Who should show up at your side
谁应该出现在你身旁

10
00:00:21,130 --> 00:00:22,417
to offer you an umbrella?
给你一把雨伞呢？

11
00:00:22,417 --> 00:00:25,052
The same guy from the football game.
就是足球赛那个讨厌鬼

12
00:00:25,052 --> 00:00:26,489
Do you change your mind about him
你会改变你对他的印象吗？

13
00:00:26,489 --> 00:00:28,213
based on this second encounter,
根据你们第二次相遇

14
00:00:28,213 --> 00:00:29,709
or do you go with your first impression
还是你依旧相信你的第一印象

15
00:00:29,709 --> 00:00:31,907
and write him off?

16
00:00:31,907 --> 00:00:34,298
Research in social psychology suggests
社会心理学的研究指出

17
00:00:34,298 --> 00:00:37,112
that we're quick to form lasting impressions of others
我们很快就能对他人产生长久印象

18
00:00:37,112 --> 00:00:39,020
based on their behaviors.
依据他人的行为

19
00:00:39,020 --> 00:00:41,314
We manage to do this with little effort,
我们很自然就这么做

20
00:00:41,314 --> 00:00:43,310
inferring stable character traits
从单一行为举止

21
00:00:43,310 --> 00:00:44,647
from a single behavior,
推论出长久的人格特质

22
00:00:44,647 --> 00:00:45,481
like a harsh word
像是说了脏话

23
00:00:45,481 --> 00:00:46,974
or a clumsy step.
或是犯了很傻的错误

24
00:00:46,974 --> 00:00:48,733
Using our impressions as guides,
我们用印象做为指引

25
00:00:48,733 --> 00:00:50,040
we can accurately predict
能够准确的预测

26
00:00:50,040 --> 00:00:53,187
how people are going to behave in the future.
这些人在未来会有什么样的举止

27
00:00:53,187 --> 00:00:54,075
Armed with the knowledge
有了这种知识

28
00:00:54,075 --> 00:00:55,462
the guy from the football game
足球比赛的那个家伙

29
00:00:55,462 --> 00:00:57,293
was a jerk the first time you met him,
你第一次遇见他，觉得他是个混蛋

30
00:00:57,293 --> 00:00:59,793
you might expect more of the same down the road.
你可能会觉得他以后也是个混蛋

31
00:00:59,793 --> 00:01:01,674
If so, you might choose to avoid him
要是这样，如果下一次你看到他

32
00:01:01,674 --> 00:01:03,009
the next time you see him.
你会选择避开他

33
00:01:03,009 --> 00:01:05,293
That said, we can change our impressions
换言之，我们会改变印象

34
00:01:05,293 --> 00:01:07,337
in light of new information.
因为我们得到新的信息

35
00:01:07,337 --> 00:01:09,873
Behavioral researchers have identified
行为研究员指出

36
00:01:09,873 --> 00:01:12,210
consistent patterns that seem to guide
这种持续模式似乎会引导着

37
00:01:12,210 --> 00:01:14,627
this process of impression updating.
我们处理印象的方向

38
00:01:14,627 --> 00:01:17,014
On one hand, learning very negative,
一方面，知道关于某人非常负面

39
00:01:17,014 --> 00:01:19,714
highly immoral information about someone
非常不道德的信息

40
00:01:19,714 --> 00:01:21,435
typically has a stronger impact
基本上会有更强的影响

41
00:01:21,435 --> 00:01:25,521
than learning very positive, highly moral information.
相对于得知某人有非常正面、道德的信息

42
00:01:25,521 --> 00:01:27,796
So, unfortunately for our new friend
所以，我们足球场的新朋友

43
00:01:27,796 --> 00:01:28,821
from the football game,
很不幸的

44
00:01:28,821 --> 00:01:30,243
his bad behavior at the game
他在球场的坏行为

45
00:01:30,243 --> 00:01:33,070
might outweigh his good behavior at the park.
可能比他在公园的好行为还要强烈

46
00:01:33,070 --> 00:01:35,628
Research suggests that this bias occurs
研究指出之所以有这种偏见

47
00:01:35,628 --> 00:01:38,828
because immoral behaviors are more diagnostic,
是因为从不道德的行为就能见微知着

48
00:01:38,828 --> 00:01:39,875
or revealing,
或是能比较真实

49
00:01:39,875 --> 00:01:42,043
of a person's true character.
显露出一个人真正的个性

50
00:01:42,043 --> 00:01:43,877
Okay, so by this logic,
好，依据这样的逻辑

51
00:01:43,877 --> 00:01:46,253
bad is always stronger than good
当有新的印象出现时

52
00:01:46,253 --> 00:01:47,923
when it comes to updating.
坏的效果比好的效果来得强烈

53
00:01:47,923 --> 00:01:49,754
Well, not necessarily.
不过，也不尽然如此

54
00:01:49,754 --> 00:01:51,882
Certain types of learning don't seem to lead
特定几种的学习似乎并不会

55
00:01:51,882 --> 00:01:54,208
to this sort of negativity bias.
导向这种负面偏见

56
00:01:54,208 --> 00:01:57,431
When learning about another person's abilities and competencies,
举例来说

57
00:01:57,431 --> 00:01:58,297
for instance,

58
00:01:58,297 --> 00:01:59,880
this bias flips.
这偏见就完全不相同

59
00:01:59,880 --> 00:02:01,348
It's actually the positive information
事实上这种正面的信息

60
00:02:01,348 --> 00:02:03,631
that gets weighted more heavily.
会来得更重要

61
00:02:03,631 --> 00:02:05,128
Let's go back to that football game.
让我们再回到足球场

62
00:02:05,128 --> 00:02:06,624
If a player scores a goal,
足球员射门得分

63
00:02:06,624 --> 00:02:08,292
it ultimately has a stronger impact
这最后会有个更强的影响

64
00:02:08,292 --> 00:02:10,200
on your impression of their skills
加深你对他们球技的印象

65
00:02:10,200 --> 00:02:11,959
than if they miss the net.
比起他们没有得分的话

66
00:02:11,959 --> 00:02:13,902
The two sides of the updating story
这两种改变印象的故事

67
00:02:13,902 --> 00:02:16,209
are ultimately quite consistent.
在最后都满有关联性

68
00:02:16,209 --> 00:02:18,310
Overall, behaviors that are perceived
总的来说

69
00:02:18,310 --> 00:02:20,542
as being less frequent are also the ones
在形成以及更新印象时

70
00:02:20,542 --> 00:02:23,379
that people tend to weigh more heavily
人们对不太常出现的行为

71
00:02:23,379 --> 00:02:25,627
when forming and updating impressions,
印象会比较深刻

72
00:02:25,627 --> 00:02:26,914
highly immoral actions
或是非常不道德的行为

73
00:02:26,914 --> 00:02:29,293
and highly competent actions.
还有非常令人满意的行为的时候

74
00:02:29,293 --> 00:02:32,004
So, what's happening at the level of the brain
所以，当大脑在更新印象的时候

75
00:02:32,004 --> 00:02:33,874
when we're updating our impressions?
这中间到底发生了什么事？

76
00:02:33,874 --> 00:02:35,257
Using fMRI,
透过 fMRI

77
00:02:35,257 --> 00:02:37,878
or functional Magnetic Resonance Imaging,
也就是功能性磁振造影

78
00:02:37,878 --> 00:02:39,294
researchers have identified
研究员指出

79
00:02:39,294 --> 00:02:41,478
an extended network of brain regions
有一块大脑区域延伸出的网络

80
00:02:41,478 --> 00:02:43,213
that respond to new information
对于和第一印象不同的

81
00:02:43,213 --> 00:02:46,104
that's inconsistent with initial impressions.
新信息会有反应

82
00:02:46,104 --> 00:02:48,296
These include areas typically associated
这些区块基本上都和

83
00:02:48,296 --> 00:02:49,574
with social cognition,
社会认知

84
00:02:49,574 --> 00:02:50,652
attention,
注意力

85
00:02:50,652 --> 00:02:52,465
and cognitive control.
以及认知控制有关

86
00:02:52,465 --> 00:02:54,568
Moreover, when updating impressions
此外，更新印象的时候

87
00:02:54,568 --> 00:02:56,570
based on people's behaviors,
若是以行为做基础

88
00:02:56,570 --> 00:02:59,709
activity in the ventrolateral prefrontal cortex
在腹侧前额叶皮质区

89
00:02:59,709 --> 00:03:02,061
and the superior temporal sulcus
以及上侧颞叶沟的活动

90
00:03:02,061 --> 00:03:03,494
correlates with perceptions
和我们所认为

91
00:03:03,494 --> 00:03:07,879
of how frequently those behaviors occur in daily life.
那些行为在生活中出现的频率有关

92
00:03:07,879 --> 00:03:10,290
In other words, the brain seems to be tracking
换言之，大脑似乎会根据

93
00:03:10,290 --> 00:03:13,180
low-level, statistical properties of behavior
统计中较低机率的行为特征

94
00:03:13,180 --> 00:03:15,900
in order to make complex decisions
针对他人的个性

95
00:03:15,900 --> 00:03:17,423
regarding other people's character.
做出复杂的决定

96
00:03:17,423 --> 00:03:18,461
It needs to decide
大脑需要决定

97
00:03:18,461 --> 00:03:20,642
is this person's behavior typical
这个人的行为合乎常理吗？

98
00:03:20,642 --> 00:03:22,483
or is it out of the ordinary?
还是违背常理？

99
00:03:22,483 --> 00:03:23,309
In the situation
在那个情况

100
00:03:23,309 --> 00:03:26,312
with the obnoxious-football-fan-turned-good-samaritan,
讨厌的足球迷最后成了好心人

101
00:03:26,312 --> 00:03:27,479
your brain says,
你的大脑说：

102
00:03:27,479 --> 00:03:28,649
"Well, in my experience,
「嗯，根据我的经验

103
00:03:28,649 --> 00:03:31,782
pretty much anyone would lend someone their umbrella,
很多人都可以借别人雨伞

104
00:03:31,782 --> 00:03:34,452
but the way this guy acted at the football game,
但是这个人在足球场的举止

105
00:03:34,452 --> 00:03:36,297
that was unusual."
却只有他会这样。」

106
00:03:36,297 --> 00:03:39,247
And so, you decide to go with your first impression.
所以，你还是决定相信第一印象

107
00:03:39,247 --> 00:03:40,985
There's a good moral in this data:
有个不错的道德故事和这资料有关：

108
00:03:40,985 --> 00:03:43,412
your brain, and by extension you,
你的大脑，延伸出去就是你

109
00:03:43,412 --> 00:03:44,794
might care more about
会比较在乎

110
00:03:44,794 --> 00:03:46,548
the very negative, immoral things
另一个人所做的非常负面

111
00:03:46,548 --> 00:03:47,792
another person has done
非常不道德的事情

112
00:03:47,792 --> 00:03:50,665
compared to the very positive, moral things,
而非十分正面且道德的事

113
00:03:50,665 --> 00:03:52,194
but it's a direct result
但这个直接的结果

114
00:03:52,194 --> 00:03:55,693
of the comparative rarity of those bad behaviors.
存在于相对及少数的坏行为之中

115
00:03:55,693 --> 00:03:58,329
We're more used to people being basically good,
我们比较习惯他人友善

116
00:03:58,329 --> 00:04:00,671
like taking time to help a stranger in need.
像是找时间去帮助需要的人

117
00:04:00,671 --> 00:04:04,200
In this context, bad might be stronger than good,
这种情况下，坏行为比好行为更强烈

118
00:04:04,200 --> 00:04:06,803
but only because good is more plentiful.
只是因为好行为占多数

119
00:04:06,803 --> 00:04:08,828
Think about the last time you judged someone
想一下你上一次根据他人行为

120
00:04:08,828 --> 00:04:10,135
based on their behavior,
而评断某人的时候

121
00:04:10,135 --> 00:04:11,843
especially a time when you really feel
尤其是当你真心觉得

122
00:04:11,843 --> 00:04:14,270
like you changed your mind about someone.
你想改变你对某人印象的时候

123
00:04:14,270 --> 00:04:15,720
Was the behavior that caused you
那种让你会

124
00:04:15,720 --> 00:04:16,899
to update your impression
改变印象的行为

125
00:04:16,899 --> 00:04:19,203
something you'd expect anyone to do,
是你认为大家都能做的

126
00:04:19,203 --> 00:04:22,398
or was it something totally out of the ordinary?
还是只有少数人才会做的？
